fresh perspectives on the Great War and its legacy at the local, national, and international levels. More importantly, it showcases exciting new research on the experiences and memories of “forgotten” participants who have often been ignored in dominant narratives or national histories. Contributors to this international study highlight the transnational character of memory-making in the Great War’s aftermath. No single memory of the war has prevailed, but many symbols, rituals, and expressions of memory connect seemingly disparate communities and wartime experiences. With groundbreaking new research on the role of Aboriginal peoples, ethnic minorities, women, artists, historians, and writers in shaping these expressions of memory, this book will be of great interest to readers from a variety of national and academic backgrounds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryzCanada. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aWar and societyzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vArt and the war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xArt and the war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xMonumentszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanada. 4aHistory. 4aHistory: Military History. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh1 aAbram, Zachary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aActon, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBullard, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaktsiris, Mary G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnelly, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFacknitz, Mark A.R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodd, Thomas, econtributor.